# {{PROJECT_NAME}} — environment variables (example)
#
# Copy this file to `.env` (or `.env.local`) and fill in real values. The real file is gitignored
# (see .gitignore: `.env`, `.env.*`, except this `.env.example`). Never commit secrets.
#
# This is the onboarding contract: every credential the app needs has a documented slot here, with a
# placeholder value — so a new machine knows exactly what to provide. Keep it in sync with the code;
# add a line the moment a new secret is introduced (house standard: secrets are server-side only).

# ── App ─────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
NODE_ENV=development
# APP_URL=http://localhost:3000

# ── Data store ({{STACK_DATA}}) ─────────────────────────────────────
# (to define: the data-store connection + keys this project needs — fill during Epic 01.3 "Secrets &
#  environment". e.g. DATABASE_URL, a least-privilege read role, a service key kept server-side only.)
# DATABASE_URL=

# ── Backend / hosting ({{STACK_BACKEND}} on {{STACK_HOSTING}}) ───────
# (to define: API keys / service credentials for the backend + host. Prod-only secrets must never
#  appear in non-prod env files.)

# ── AI ({{STACK_AI}}) ───────────────────────────────────────────────
# (to define: model-provider API key(s), only if this project uses AI. Remove this block if not.)
# ANTHROPIC_API_KEY=

# ── CI / automation ─────────────────────────────────────────────────
# (to define: any secret the CI status-guard or scheduled jobs need.)
